I was on my way to Awendo Green Stadium on Tuesday afternoon when I encountered two little girls, perhaps on their way to collect firewood. They were both barefoot but one of them was wearing a tattered glove on her right hand, and the other was hauling a deflated ball from a short distance.
It made for a lovely scene watching the glove wearer try hard to catch the deflated ball at every instance, diving haphazardly to the right and to the left, obviously imitating someone.





They didn’t stay at their game for too long but as I stood watching them play, I kept wondering: Who was it who sparked the taller girl’s interest in football? Why the particular love for goalkeeping? Whose jersey does she own? Who does she model her game on?
But no dialogue was needed to tell the narrative. Those were ambitious girls with the spirit and ambition to play and succeed in football, but even at age 10, the odds are stacked so high against them that it seems almost foolhardy to expect them to realize their football dreams.
That same evening, I stumbled upon an article on Kahawa Tungu where one Phoebe Ndege had been featured. Phoebe was once a talented and passionate footballer, but she is now now based in the US studying electrical engineering. The tone of the story portrayed Phoebe as a successful former footballer, but I couldn’t help but worry about the thousands of girls countrywide who have had to abandon their football passion in pursuit of alternative success.  



