To do that, however, deliberate efforts must be undertaken to make the climb to the top easier for passionate girls. It won’t be a bad idea for football stakeholders to hold regular talent identification camps in rural areas. That could be where the talent lies.
In happier news, the Royal Morocco Football Federation has rolled out a four-year project worth Sh600 million ($6 million) in an attempt to grow women’s football in Morocco. A minimum wage concept has been introduced whereby clubs will be expected to pay players a minimum of Sh35,000 ($350) in the topflight league and Sh25,000 for the second tier players.
Also, the minimum salary for coaches in the first division will be Sh50,000 ($500) while their counterparts in the second division will earn not less than Sh35,000 ($350).
They have also revived the women’s league governing body (Ligue Nationale de Football Feminin), and have proposed that all clubs set up Under-15 and Under-17 teams which will act as incubators for the national side.
We can only hope that these measures will be implemented to the letter. He served in former president Daniel Moi's cabinet. BBI secretariat cleaned up the 5.2 million signatures that endorsed the Bill, and weeded out 800,000 that had entry irregularities. This comes days after he collapsed at a hotel in Nairobi and was placed under intensive care at Nairobi Hospital.